    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Visualisation**\n",
        "\n",
        "After bootstrapping the data, Sameer had to decide the best way to display these results for easy visualisation and interpretation. A bar graph allowed for an accessible way to view the new, smoother temperature distributions. Sameer had to decide on a bin size to divide the data up into that was small enough to be meanigful but large enough to plot cleanly. The rule of thumb of using the square root of the sample size worked perfectly here. Sameer also plotted the data using red and blue distribution curves on the same graph, allowing for direct comparison between locations and keeping it accessible for colourblind viewers. This was probably the key decision regarding visualisation, and for me is a far superior choice than plotting the two locations on seperate graphs with potentially different scales as this would have made comparison much harder."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "tsCoCsqtg0i7"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
          "height": 564
        },
        "id": "b77d063a",
        "outputId": "4c6719ee-8d58-429e-d729-8cbb2052e6e3"
      },
      "source": [
        "import seaborn as sns # Import seaborn for enhanced visualizations.\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt # Import matplotlib.pyplot for plotting.\n",
        "\n",
        "bar_Canberra_cleaned = bar_Canberra[~np.isnan(bar_Canberra)] # Remove NaN values from Canberra's bootstrapped means.\n",
        "bar_Ulladulla_cleaned = bar_Ulladulla[~np.isnan(bar_Ulladulla)] # Remove NaN values from Ulladulla's bootstrapped means.\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6)) # Create a new figure with a specified size.\n",
        "\n",
        "num_bins = int(np.sqrt(100000)) # Calculate the number of bins based on the square root of samples.\n",
        "\n",
        "sns.histplot(bar_Canberra_cleaned, color='blue', label='Canberra', kde=True, stat='density', alpha=0.5, bins=num_bins) # Plot histogram for Canberra's bootstrapped means.\n",
        "sns.histplot(bar_Ulladulla_cleaned, color='red', label='Ulladulla', kde=True, stat='density', alpha=0.5, bins=num_bins) # Plot histogram for Ulladulla's bootstrapped means.\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.title('Distribution of Bootstrapped Mean Temperatures on 25th December') # Add a title to the plot.\n",
        "plt.xlabel('Mean Temperature (ºC)') # Label the x-axis.\n",
        "plt.ylabel('Density') # Label the y-axis.\n",
        "plt.legend() # Display the legend.\n",
        "plt.grid(True) # Add a grid to the plot.\n",
        "plt.show() # Show the generated plot."
      ],
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "display_data",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": [
              "<Figure size 1000x600 with 1 Axes>"
            ],
            "image/png": "\n"
          },
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Interpretation**\n",
        "\n",
        "Both locations have a mean temperature in the 20-30 degree celcius range, making them both good options. Ulladulla has a mean *~*23 degrees and a narrower range, making it a more reliable option. However, Canberra boasts a mean temperature of *~* 27 degrees celcius, exactly what ChatGPT said was the ideal temperature. Although Canberra has a wider range of temperatures, they follow a normal distrubution curve and even the edges of the xx confidence interval fall closer to 27 degrees than the same confidence interval of Ulladulla.\n",
        "\n",
        "This can be attributed to the effects of the coastal climate. The high heat capacity of the ocean moderates temperature change, slowing heating and cooling. Ulladulla air flow is also dominated by ocean breezes. This keeps temperature more consistent year to year and reduces the impact of extremely hot days. On the other hand, Canberra's inland location means that the ground can warm or cool much faster, and it is subject to both cooler southerly winds or hot air from inland. These factors make Canberra's climate much more variable and lead to the wider and warmer distribution evident on the graph.\n",
        "\n",
        "Ultimately, it is tough to draw conclusions about the influential climate factors based on one measurement (max temp), and both Canberra and Ulladulla will hopefully have great BBQ conditions this Chrissy."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "snUoj8LTGV4C"
      }
    },
